Headline: Qatargas LNG Production At 42M Tons By 2010 - Gulf Times
Story: LONDON (Dow Jones)--Qatar Liquefied Gas Co., otherwise known as Qatargas, will have an annual liquefied natural gas production capacity of 42 million metric tons by 2010, said Chief Executive Faisal M al-Suwaidi Saturday, according to a report in Doha-based newspaper the Gulf Times Sunday.   By then, Qatargas will be operating seven LNG trains, al-Suwaidi said. Four LNG trains are already operational in the Persian Gulf state, which has the world's third largest natural gas reserves, after Russia and Iran.   Trains four and five will start up in 2008, al-Suwaidi said, and trains six will come online in 2009 and train seven in 2010. Each of the four new trains will have an annual production capacity of 7.8 million tons.   Current LNG production capacity has reached 10 million tons a year after the removal of a number of bottlenecks in the production process last year, al-Suwaidi said.   Qatargas is a joint venture between state-owned Qatar Petroleum, Total SA (TOT), ExxonMobil Corp. (XOM), Mitsui & Co. (MITSY) and Marubeni Corp. (MARUY)   Company Web site: http://www.gulf-times.com   -London Bureau, Dow Jones Newswires; +44 (0)20 7842 9317; james.herron@dowjones.com   Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 21, 2007 07:29 ET (12:29 GMT)

Headline: REPEAT&CORRECT:WSJ: NASD OKs Regulatory Merger With NYSE
Story: (The item "=WSJ: NASD OKs Changes To Merge Securities Regs With NYSE," published at 1:02 p.m. EST, misidentified  the NASD and misstated the vote.)       By Randall Smith     Of THE WALL STREET JOURNAL     Members of the NASD have approved bylaw changes to merge securities regulation with the New York Stock Exchange.   The NASD, formerly the National Association of Securities Dealers, claimed victory with a vote of 2,671 to 1,440 despite opposition from a vocal group of dissidents who campaigned to block the merger, saying its terms would weaken the voice of small firms within NASD.   (This story and related background material will be available on The Wall Street Journal Web site, WSJ.com.)   The NASD said 64% of the 5,058 firms eligible to vote supported the by-law changes out of a total of 83% which cast votes. The result was a victory for NASD chief executive Mary Schapiro, who campaigned for the merger in a cross-country tour.   "The securities industry has embraced replacing an outdated regulatory structure with one that better serves firms and investors in a fast-changing marketplace,"  Schapiro said in a statement.   The dissidents opposing the plan had complained that instead of electing up to 15 of 18 NASD governors, small firms would elect three of 23 directors in the merged organization. The NASD offered firms a payment of $35,000 apiece if the merger was approved.   The merger had been sought for more than six years by major Wall Street firms, 200 of which were regulated and inspected by both the NYSE and the NASD, as supervised by the Securities and Exchange Commission. The big firms said the rulebooks and inspections were duplicative and at times inconsistent.   In early November, such a merger won the public endorsement of Securities and Exchange Commission chairman Christopher Cox. The plan was announced Nov. 28, and the voting deadline was last Friday Jan. 19.   Although the dissident group had won two out of three NASD governor seats up for election last year, turnout in that election was lighter, according to people familiar with the results. "I appreciate that so many NASD members took the time to study the proposal and to participate in the voting process," Schapiro added in her statement.     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 21, 2007 15:36 ET (20:36 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: Airbus Solves A380 Wiring Problems; First Delivery In Oct
Story: FRANKFURT (AP)--European Aeronautic Defence & Space Co.'s (5730.FR) aircraft maker Airbus has solved the wiring problems of its A380 "superjumbo" plane, Airbus spokesman Tore Prang said Saturday.   The first A380 has been completely wired and the aircraft's interior is being fitted, said Prang, who called it an important milestone in the production of the A380.   The first A380 should be delivered to Singapore Airlines Ltd. (S55.SG) in October, Prang said, referring to comments made by EADS Chief Executive Louis Gallois Wednesday.   Airbus had to postpone delivery of the A380 several times due to the wiring problems, triggering a crisis at parent company EADS.     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 21, 2007 08:25 ET (13:25 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: China's Dongfeng Sets 1 Mln Vehicle Output Goal In 07-Xinhua
Story: BEIJING (Dow Jones)--Chinese automaker Dongfeng Motor Corp. has set itself a target of producing 1 million vehicles for sale this year, the Xinhua News Agency reported Sunday, citing a company official.   Meeting such a goal would surpass the 932,000 vehicles that state-owned Dongfeng Motor produced and marketed last year, Xinhua said, citing the Hubei-based company's deputy Communist Party secretary, Fan Zhong.   Dongfeng Motor's 2006 production and sales performance was 27.9% higher than in 2005 and above the 25.13% on-year growth recorded by the industry as a whole last year, the report said.   Passenger vehicle sales totaled 656,000 units last year and Dongfeng Motor's commercial vehicle sales totaled 276,000, Fan was quoted as saying.   Overall, the company's revenue grew by 12.6% and its profits were up 46%, Xinhua added without providing exact figures or stating the type of profits involved.   Dongfeng Motor Corp. is the parent of Hong Kong-listed Dongfeng Motor Group Co. (0489.HK), which partners with Honda Motor Corp. (HMC), among others.   -By David Winning, Dow Jones Newswires; 8610-65885848; david.winning@dowjones.com       (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 21, 2007 04:24 ET (09:24 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: WSJA(1/22) Heard In Japan: Aging Workers Will Help Economy
Story: (From THE WALL STREET JOURNAL ASIA)     By Sebastian Moffett   Tokyo -- FOR SOME JAPANESE companies, there may be a silver lining to the nation's graying population.   The aging of society has become a byword for future economic misery in Japan and parts of Europe: As the number of retirees soars, increasing the burden on pension and health-care systems, the work force faces long-term decline, reducing an economy's ability to support the elderly.   Japan will see the most dramatic wave yet of this trend this year, when the products of its concentrated post-World War II baby boom -- which covers 1947 through 1949 -- begin to hit age 60 and retire. The country's 67 million-strong work force will decline by about 500,000 in each of the three years during which those employees reach retirement. But economists say that, at least for a few years, the effect on corporate profits could be positive.   To get an idea of the upside, consider giant phone carrier Nippon Telegraph & Telephone Corp. NTT took on new staff 30 or 40 years ago to build out Japan's telecommunications system. But for some time, fixed-line revenue has declined, and the NTT group has taken on progressively fewer workers over the years.   The workers from the big intake are now in their 50s: When NTT East Corp. and NTT West Corp. -- the group's two regional units -- and some of their outsourcing companies are combined, they have nearly 8,000 workers aged 58, according to a chart supplied by the company. But the companies have only about 1,000 workers aged 35, and a few hundred aged 25.   Because pay at big Japanese companies is in large part determined by length of service, the older workers are far more expensive. When they leave the payroll, NTT group companies' fixed costs will fall.   Natan Ramler, an analyst at Macquarie Securities, estimates that the baby-boomer retirement will reduce fixed costs at NTT East to 1.4 trillion yen ($11.5 billion) in the fiscal year ending March 31, 2008 from 1.5 trillion yen in the fiscal year ended March 31, 2006. (The company wouldn't provide details of workers' average pay.) "It's very clear that NTT will be making cost savings," says Mr. Ramler.   But that still doesn't make the company a great bet for investors. Partly because NTT East's businesses are so old, Mr. Ramler thinks its revenue will decline to two trillion yen from 2.1 trillion yen over the same period. He forecasts a small rise in profitability -- to 73 billion yen in the year ending March 2008, from 66 billion yen in March 2006.   Future prospects, too, are limited, says Mr. Ramler, because the only way to increase revenue is through huge investments in expensive technologies, such as fiber optics.   NTT group's share price was at 614,000 yen on the Tokyo Stock Exchange at the close of trade on Friday, but Mr. Ramler thinks it will slide to 490,000 yen over the next 12 months. The baby-boomer retirement is "a very positive development," he says, but not enough to offset other problems at the business.   The same logic applies to other industries that grew quickly three or four decades ago. Baby boomers account for about 16% of steel companies' personnel costs, compared with just 9% for financial companies, a December report by Goldman Sachs said. In transport companies, such as railroads, as well as telecommunications companies, they account for 14%.   The workers that replace the retiring boomers will mostly be younger -- and in many cases hired on cheaper terms on short-term contracts. Some companies will rehire the older workers who have just retired, but at far lower rates of pay. Overall, according to Goldman Sachs calculations, the decrease in wage costs will boost corporate earnings by two percentage points a year in each of the next three fiscal years ending in March 2008, 2009 and 2010.   To be sure, paying less to workers also means lower overall personal income and, eventually, less national consumption. But at least for the next few years, economists say consumption is unlikely to be hit by the mass retirement. The boomers have amassed savings and many will get big lump-sum retirement payments. Just using a bit of this wealth could offset the reduction in income for a while.   However, in five or 10 years, Japan faces a serious labor shortage, and keeping the economy growing will require wrenching change, such as gains in production per worker, bigger numbers of working women and large-scale immigration.   Longer term, demographic change could lead to a "potentially large decline of the potential rate of growth," says Tetsufumi Yamakawa, chief economist at Goldman Sachs. But first, he says, "corporate earnings will go up because of the replacement of labor by younger generation people."     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 21, 2007 16:30 ET (21:30 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: NZ PRESS: Tindall May Come Up With Fresh Warehouse Bid
Story: WELLINGTON (Dow Jones)--The Warehouse Group (WHS.NZ) founder Stephen Tindall could get involved in a new takeover bid for the company alongside supermarket operator Foodstuffs and private equity investor Pacific Equity Partners, the Sunday Star Times reported, quoting unnamed sources.   The report said the three may be seeking to work together on a deal to rival the expected bid from Australian supermarket giant Woolworths Ltd. (WOW.AU), which along with Foodstuffs has applied for regulatory clearance to buy 100% of The Warehouse.   Tindall controls 51% of The Warehouse, New Zealand's biggest discount retailer. Foodstuffs and Woolworths, which each control a 10% stake, have said they are interested in The Warehouse, but they haven't yet made a formal bid.     Newspaper web site:  http://www.stuff.co.nz     -Wellington Bureau, Dow Jones Newswires; 64-4-471-5990; djnews.wellington@dowjones.com     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 21, 2007 14:30 ET (19:30 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: China Industrial Bank To Raise Up To CNY16B In A-Shr IPO -2
Story: Industrial Bank said 300 million shares, or 30% of the offering, will be sold to strategic investors. The institutional tranche will total 300.3 million shares, and 400.7 million shares, or 40% of the IPO, will be sold to retail investors.   It also said final pricing will be disclosed Jan. 26.   Industrial Bank, in which Hang Seng Bank Ltd. (0011.HK) holds a 16% stake, is set to become mainland China's eighth listed bank.   Institutional subscription is scheduled for Monday and Tuesday, while retail subscription will take place on Tuesday, the bank said.   Industrial Bank said it will use the proceeds of the IPO to increase its capital adequacy and open more outlets.   As of Sept. 30, its capital adequacy ratio was 8.41%, above the regulatory minimum of 8%.   Industrial Bank had a network of 369 branches nationwide as of Jun. 30, putting it in the mid-range of Chinese commercial banks. In comparison, Industrial & Commercial Bank of China Ltd., the country's biggest bank by assets, had a network of 18,038 branches across the country as of 2005.   Industrial Bank's net profit in the first half of 2006 was CNY1.75 billion, compared with CNY2.46 billion for full-year 2005.   Hang Seng Bank, a unit of HSBC Holdings PLC (0005.HK), is the bank's second-largest shareholder after the Fujian provincial government's finance bureau, which holds 25.5%.   Among Industrial Bank's other foreign investors are a unit of Singapore's Government Investment Corp., which holds 5%, and the World Bank's International Finance Corp., which has a 4% stake.   BOC International (China) Ltd. is the lead underwriter on the IPO.     -Rose Yu and Zheng Jin contributed to this story, Dow Jones Newswires; 8621 6120-1200; rose.yu@dowjones.com     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 21, 2007 09:07 ET (14:07 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: British Airways Cabin Crew To Strike Jan 29-31, Union Says
Story: LONDON (AP)--Thousands of British Airways PLC (BAB) cabin crew are to stage a three-day strike following the breakdown of talks aimed at resolving a row over sickness absence, pay and staffing, their union said Sunday.   Stewards and stewardesses will walk out from Jan. 29 to 31, the Transport and General Worker's Union said. The union notified BA of its intention to call out cabin crew on strike again on Feb. 6-8 and Feb. 12-14 if the dispute isn't resolved.   British Airways criticized the union, saying the strikes would cause massive disruption for passengers and further damage to the airline, which has been hit in recent months by security and weather problems.   The union held several meetings with British Airways executives last week to avert the strike action, following a 96% vote for strike by the 11,000 cabin crew workers.   But the union said that negotiations had broken down.   Jack Dromey, deputy general secretary of the union, accused BA of failing to enter into a dialogue with the union on compromise proposals, accusing them of provoking the strike action.   "Our members are fed up with being bullied into coming to work when sick and with the divisions caused by poverty levels of new entrant pay scales," Dromy said.   "They see customer care being cut and the airline's reputation damaged by bungling management.   "BA now have seven days to take their responsibility seriously and work with the union to avoid disruption to services and inconvenience to passengers. We are ready to resume talks at any time," he said.   The cabin crew have accused management of forcing them to work when they were ill, following the implementation of a new policy on sickness pay that was introduced 18 months ago.   BA chief executive Willie Walsh said the company was disappointed by the union's decision but remained focussed on finding a solution that it hoped would prevent the strikes.   "Despite its public rhetoric, the union in private remains resolute in its refusal to talk with us about any degree of change for our cabin crew," Walsh said.   Walsh insisted the airline hadn't imposed any changes about sickness absence but stressed it wanted to negotiate new ways of working with its cabin crew to help put the airline in better shape to succeed in the "highly competitive" industry.   Walsh said the union had made additions to its earlier demands over a return to the "excessive" levels of sickness absence. He said the union was also demanding a "significant" pay rise for its members,   In a statement the airline said its new sickness policy had reduced average levels of absence among cabin crew to 12 days a year from 22 days.   Customers who had booked flights between Monday, Jan. 29 and Friday, Feb. 16 would be allowed to change the date of their flights, BA said.     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 21, 2007 14:17 ET (19:17 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: UK PRESS: BBC Set To Start Selling Internet Ads Overseas
Story: LONDON (Dow Jones)--The British Broadcasting Corp., the U.K. broadcaster which is funded by a public license fee, is set to open a New York-based sales office as it prepares to sell advertising space on its Web site for overseas users, the Sunday Telegraph reports.   The Web site, bbc.co.uk, attracts 40 million overseas visitors a year and the corporation, which in the U.K. is banned from selling advertising, wants to direct these users to an international site which will be able to sell advertising, the paper claims.   The newspaper quotes Luke Bradley-Jones, the head of strategy at BBC Worldwide, the corporation's commercial arm, saying the BBC wants to grow its international business, but he isn't quoted on the advertising issue. BBC Worldwide didn't respond to requests for comment.   Newspaper Web site: http://www.telegraph.co.uk   -London Bureau, Dow Jones Newswires; +44 (0)20 7842 9320     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 21, 2007 11:55 ET (16:55 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: UK PRESS: Report Links BP Cost Cutting To Refinery Blast
Story: LONDON (Dow Jones)--A report by the U.S. Chemical Safety Board, or CSB, into a fatal explosion at BP PLC's (BP) Texas City Refinery March 23, 2005 will make direct links between cost cutting and the cause of the blast, the U.K.'s Observer newspaper reported Sunday.   Carolyn Merritt, chairwoman of the CSB, told the paper: "Budget cuts had an impact on safety and that impact on safety had a causal relationship with what happened on March 23. We have an ironclad case for the impact of cost cutting on safety. We will be making those conclusions in our report.   "Complacency and disregard for the inherent danger of what was being done was at every level of the organization to the very top...The message that was communicated was that cost cutting and maximizing profits was the most important thing."   The report is scheduled to be published March 20.   CSB officials estimate that between 1992 and 2000, maintenance spending at Texas City fell 84%. BP took over running of the refinery from U.S. oil company Amoco when the two merged in 1998.   A BP spokesman told the Observer: "We have always said that budget cuts had no impact on safety. The (Baker) panel said it could not find a link."   Company Web site: http://observer.guardian.co.uk   -London Bureau, Dow Jones Newswires; +44 (0)20 7842 9317; james.herron@dowjones.com     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 21, 2007 06:10 ET (11:10 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: UK PRESS: BSkyB's James Murdoch To Stand Down Summer 2007
Story: LONDON (Dow Jones)--British Sky Broadcasting Group PLC (BSY) Chief Executive James Murdoch will step down in summer 2007 to be replaced by Tom Mockridge, the CEO of Sky Italia, the Mail on Sunday claims, without citing its sources.   The paper claims Murdoch, the son of Rupert Murdoch, chairman and chief executive of BSkyB's 39% owner News Corp. (NWS), will take an executive role within News Corp. Sky Italia is a unit of News Corp.   New Zealander Mockridge is a former chief executive at News Corp.'s Australian pay-television unit Foxtel.   A BSkyB spokesman said the company never commented on speculation of this kind.   Newspaper Web site: http://www.mailonsunday.co.uk   -London Bureau, Dow Jones Newswires; +44 (0)20 7842 9320     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 21, 2007 11:28 ET (16:28 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: UK PRESS: BP CEO To Meet James Baker To Discuss Safety
Story: LONDON (Dow Jones)--Tony Hayward, the incoming Chief Executive of BP Group (BP), will this week meet James Baker to discuss how to implement recommendations in the former U.S. Secretary of State's report into safety lapses at the company, the Sunday Telegraph reports without citing sources.   Baker's report, published last week, was prompted by a fatal explosion at a BP oil refinery in Texas and was highly critical of safety procedures in the company's U.S. refineries.   BP couldn't be contacted for comment.   Newspaper Web site: http://www.telegraph.co.uk   -London Bureau, Dow Jones Newswires; +44 (0)20 7842 9320     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 21, 2007 12:31 ET (17:31 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: Dai Nippon Print To Build Photomask Plant In Taiwan-Nikkei
Story: TOKYO (Nikkei)--Dai Nippon Printing Co. (7912.TO) plans to invest Y20 billion to construct a photomask plant in Taiwan, with mass production expected to begin in September 2008, The Nikkei learned Sunday.   Output will be supplied mainly to semiconductor factories in Taiwan, which hosts the world's largest number of cutting-edge plants using 300mm wafers. Dai Nippon expects demand for photomasks to grow at a time when chipmakers, including Elpida Memory Inc. (6665.TO), plan to build more Taiwanese plants, The Nikkei reported in its Monday morning edition.   Dai Nippon has already acquired about 10,000 sq. meters of land in northern Taiwan to build the new factory. Construction is slated for April, with the plant's operation expected to begin in May 2008.   Sales at the plant are projected at Y5 billion for the year ending March 2009 and Y12 billion the following year.   Following Japan and Italy, Taiwan is Dai Nippon's third mass production site for photomasks.   The global market for photomasks is estimated at slightly over Y300 billion, with Toppan Printing Co. (7911.TO) holding the largest share of around 30%.  Dai Nippon, ranked second with a market share of about 20%, aims to take on Toppan Printing by supplying customers in Taiwan more quickly.     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 21, 2007 14:25 ET (19:25 GMT)

Headline: Canada Fin Min: China Says Canada Banks Are Too Conservative
Story: OTTAWA (Dow Jones)--China thinks Canadian banks haven't been aggressive enough in that country and wants them to participate more in the initial public offerings of their lenders, Canadian Finance Minister Jim Flaherty said Sunday.   Flaherty, who has been in China since Wednesday to promote ties and seek more access for Canadian banks in that country, met with his counterpart Jin Renqing, People's Bank of China Governor Zhou Xiaochuan, and regulators from the financial services sector during his visit.   "One of the things I heard from officials in China is that our financial services sector, particularly our banks, have probably been too conservative, not aggressive enough in the China market," Flaherty told Canadian reporters in a conference call from Shanghai.   He noted that there have been several successful IPOs by Chinese banks in the last year. "And the comment was made to me (by the Chinese officials) that perhaps the Canadian banks should be less conservative in participating in some of those large IPOs," he said.    Flaherty said Canadian insurers Manulife Financial Corp. (MFC) and Sun Life Financial Inc. (SLF) have been "fairly aggressive" in China and have "met with quite substantial market participation."   "So I think there may be something to be learned there from the comments of the officials, that our banks perhaps ought to be more aggressive in this market place," he added.   Flaherty said he told the officials that Canada welcomed Chinese investments. China is keenly interested in Canada's natural resources sector.   On Canada's part, its businesses, including the financial sector, are seeking growth opportunities in China's services sector.   "So there's lots of room to do business together," Flaherty said.   He added that he hopes to have Jin and Zhou visit Canada in the next year.     -Nirmala Menon, Dow Jones Newswires; 613-237-0668; nirmala.menon@dowjones.com     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 21, 2007 11:41 ET (16:41 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: GERMAN PRESS: Ford To Expand Russian Production Capacity
Story: FRANKFURT (Dow Jones)--Ford Motor Co. (F) intends to expand its production capacity in Russia in 2007 by 20% on the year, weekly magazine Automotive News Europe reports in an extract ahead of full publication Monday.   The move is intended to meet rising demand in Russia and Ford expects Russian sales to increase by up to 30% as a result, the paper reports, citing Ford Russia President Henrik Nenzen.   Ford intends to produce 75,000 Ford Focus models in Russia in 2007, the magazine says.   Magazine Web site: http://www.autonews.com   -Frankfurt Bureau, Dow Jones Newswires; 49-69-29725-500     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 21, 2007 09:33 ET (14:33 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Story: LONDON (Dow Jones)--The banks that backed the return of U.K. retailer Debenhams PLC (DEB.LN) to the public markets have struggled to refinance most of its GBP1 billion-plus debt, the Sunday Telegraph reports, citing unnamed fixed-income trading sources.   The four banks that arranged the refinancing - HBOS PLC (HBOS.LN), Royal Bank of Scotland Group PLC (RBS.LN), Lloyds TSB Group PLC (LYG) and Barclays PLC (BCS) - are still holding most of the debt, the paper claims.   Debenhams was bought by private equity groups Texas Pacific Group and CVC Capital Partners in 2003 for GBP1.7 billion. Debenhams' 2006 IPO was widely considered disappointing and the newspaper claims this has "rubbed off" on the company's debt. It claims that under normal circumstances, the debt would have been syndicated within a couple of months of the IPO.   Lloyds TSB and Royal Bank of Scotland declined to comment. HBOS didn't return calls seeking comment and Barclays couldn't be contacted.   Newspaper Web site: http://www.telegraph.co.uk   -London Bureau, Dow Jones Newswires; +44 (0)20 7842 9320     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 21, 2007 11:58 ET (16:58 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: UK PRESS: Woolworths Asks Its Suppliers For Money
Story: LONDON (Dow Jones)--Woolworth Group PLC (WLW.LN), has written to suppliers to ask for money to help cover store upgrades and marketing costs, the Mail on Sunday reports, citing unnamed suppliers.   The newspaper said Tony Page, a Woolworth executive, wrote to 700 suppliers asking them for a "retrospective payment," which the report said is unusual.   Woolworth didn't respond to requests seeking comment.     Newspaper Web site: http://www.mailonsunday.co.uk     -London Bureau, Dow Jones Newswires; +44 (0)20 7842 9320     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 21, 2007 12:30 ET (17:30 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: TAIWAN PRESS:Kinpo Grp Sees 07 Rev Up 30% To Near US$21B
Story: TAIPEI (Dow Jones)--Taiwan electronics conglomerate Kinpo Group expects its full-year revenue will grow more than 30% in 2007 to nearly US$21 billion, or around NT$670 billion, the Economic Daily News reported Sunday, citing group Chairman Rock Hsu.   The group-wide revenue growth will be supported in part by Kinpo unit Compal Electronics Inc. (2324.TW), the world's second-largest notebook computer maker by shipments and a key member in the group, the newspaper said.   Compal Electronics President Ray Chen said the company's notebook computer shipments will exceed 20 million units this year, which would surpass the shipment target of its rival Quanta Computer Inc. (2382.TW) for the same period, the newspaper said.       Newspaper Web site: http://www.udn.com       -By Taipei bureau, Dow Jones Newswires; 8862-2502-2557; djnews.taipei@dowjones.com     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 21, 2007 01:18 ET (06:18 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: Singer Tom Jones Urges Burberry Against Factory Closure
Story: LONDON (AP)--Welsh singer Tom Jones has joined a campaign to pressure luxury goods maker Burberry Group PLC (BRBY.LN) not to close a factory near his south Wales birthplace.   Burberry, whose distinctive check pattern is considered quintessentially British, last year said it planned to close its factory in Treorchy, Wales, with the loss of 300 jobs, and switch production to China. It still has two other factories in Britain.   Jones, 66, who grew up in nearby Pontypridd, said that "as a local boy I know how important this factory has been to the community" in Wales' impoverished Rhondda valley.   "I therefore urge the Burberry management to withdraw their plans to close their Treorchy factory," Jones said in a statement released Sunday by the "Keep Burberry British" campaign.   Other celebrities have called on Burberry to keep the factory open, including Welsh actors Ioan Gruffudd and Rhys Ifans, opera singer Bryn Terfel and actress Emma Thompson.   Local lawmaker Chris Bryant said he planned to introduce a motion in Parliament this week calling for Burberry to lose its royal warrant if it moved production from Wales. Royal warrants allow businesses to sport a crest describing them as official suppliers to the royal family. Burberry holds two, one from Queen Elizabeth II and one from Prince Charles.   Burberry Group, which last week reported a 22% increase in third-quarter revenue, has said it has found "no commercially viable alternative" to closing the factory.     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 21, 2007 07:58 ET (12:58 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: UK PRESS: Banks Subpoenaed In US Online Gaming Probe
Story: LONDON (Dow Jones)--Dresdner Kleinwort, Credit Suisse Group (CS), Deutsche Bank AG (DB) and HSBC Holdings PLC (HBC) are among banks to have been served with subpoenas by the U.S. Department of Justice as part of an ongoing investigation into illegal online gambling in the U.S., the Sunday Times and Sunday Telegraph report, without citing sources.   Many online gaming companies were headquartered in London to avoid laws banning online gaming until the U.S. government late last year signed legislation banning financial services companies from processing payments to Internet gambling groups.   Deutsche Bank and Credit Suisse declined to comment on the issue, while Dresdner Kleinwort and HSBC couldn't immediately be reached for comment.   Newspaper Web site: http://www.timesonline.co.uk   Newspaper Web site: http://www.telegraph.co.uk   -London Bureau, Dow Jones Newswires; +44 (0)20 7842 9320     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 21, 2007 09:28 ET (14:28 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: 'Stomp The Yard' Remains On Top Of US Weekend Box Office
Story: LOS ANGELES (AP)--The dance flick "Stomp the Yard"  retained its top spot at the box office for a second week, but a handful of small films were boosted by their success at the Golden Globes.   The Fox Searchlight film "The Last King of Scotland" was the biggest beneficiary as the studio shrewdly expanded the art house film from four theaters to 495, anticipating a good performance at the Globes. The movie took in an estimated $1.8 million from Friday to Sunday. Fox Searchlight is owned by News Corp. (NWS).   Forest Whitaker was named best actor in a drama for his portrayal of Ugandan dictator Idi Amin. He also is considered a favorite for an acting Oscar.   "The marketplace accepted the movie," said Paul Dergarabedian, president of box-office tracker Media By Numbers. "Having Forest Whitaker win for that key role really boosted the film."   "Babel," from Paramount Vantage, a division of Viacom Inc. (VIAB), increased its ticket sales 500% from last weekend after the film, an ensemble piece featuring Brad Pitt and Cate Blanchett, won best drama honors at the Globes.   The film, which initially didn't make the list of top 20 box office earners, jumped to 12th place this weekend with $2.3 million, according to studio estimates, bringing its 13-week take to $24 million).   The Miramax drama "The Queen" also got a huge lift, jumping 233% from last week to the ninth spot after its star, Helen Mirren, won two Golden Globes - one for her portrayal of Queen Elizabeth II in "The Queen," and as Queen Elizabeth I in a TV miniseries. Miramax is a division of Walt Disney Co. (DIS).   Another smaller film, the wartime fantasy "Pan's Labyrinth," from Picturehouse, a division of Time Warner Inc. (TWX), saw its weekend gross jump 118%, moving it from 18th place last week to seventh place this weekend with $4.7 million.   The film, from Mexican director Guillermo del Toro, has won numerous awards, although it lost last week in the best foreign-language film category at the Globes to the Clint Eastwood Japanese-language war film "Letters From Iwo Jima."   "Anyone who is skeptical about the positive effect a Globe win can have on a film's box office need only look at this weekend's numbers," Dergarabedian said.   Many of the films are expected to be nominated Tuesday for the Academy Awards.   Sony Screen Gems' (SNE) "Stomp the Yard," which focuses on a step competition between rival college fraternities, earned $13.3 million, narrowly beating 20th Century Fox's "Night at the Museum" with $13 million. The comedy starring Ben Stiller has made about $206 million. 20th Century Fox is owned by News Corp.   The only film to open wide this weekend, the horror movie "The Hitcher," came in fourth at the box office.   "The film is a little disappointing for us," said Jack Foley, president of distribution for Rogue Pictures. "It opened competitively in a sluggish marketplace and I think it will stick around for a few weeks anyway."   Overall, box office receipts for the top 12 films were down 20% from the same weekend last year.   Estimated ticket sales for Friday through Sunday at U.S. and Canadian theaters, according to Media By Numbers LLC. Final figures will be released Monday.   1. "Stomp the Yard," $13.3 million   2. "Night at the Museum," $13 million   3. "Dreamgirls," $8.7 million   4. "The Hitcher," $8.2 million   5. "The Pursuit of Happyness," $6.7 million   6. "Freedom Writers," $5.6 million   7. "Pan's Labyrinth," $4.7 million   8. "Children of Men," $3.7 million   9. "The Queen," $3.7 million   10. "Arthur and The Invisibles," $3.1 million     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 21, 2007 14:41 ET (19:41 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: UK PRESS: Tesco Submits Applications To Build UK Homes
Story: LONDON (Dow Jones)--Tesco PLC (TSCO.LN), the U.K.'s largest supermarket group, is moving into the house construction market with plans to oversee construction of 2,000 homes in the next three years, the Sunday Times said, without citing sources.   The newspaper said proposals have been submitted for a GBP400 million scheme in Woolwich, London, including 960 homes.   A spokeswoman for Tesco confirmed a planning application has been submitted for a development in Woolwich. She said Tesco has been involved in earlier construction projects as one of the U.K.'s largest land developers and has already been involved in selling and renting homes in the U.K.   Newspaper Web site: http://www.timesonline.co.uk   -London Bureau, Dow Jones Newswires; +44 (0)20 7842 9320     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 21, 2007 11:30 ET (16:30 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: UK PRESS: Tata, CSN Both Poised To Raise Bids For Corus
Story: LONDON (Dow Jones)--Tata Steel (500470.BY), the Indian steel maker, is poised to raise its offer for U.K. steel maker Corus Group PLC (CGA) in a bid to beat a recommended offer from Brazil's Companhia Siderurgica Nacional (SID), the Sunday Times, the Mail on Sunday and the Observer newspapers report, without citing sources.   The Sunday Times said Tata, a unit of Tata Group, will raise its offer to beat an agreed bid from CSN at 515 pence a share, valuing Corus at GBP5.9 billion including debt. The Observer believes Tata will offer around 530 pence a share, while the Mail on Sunday suggests 550 pence. The Sunday Times said Tata could offer as much as 600 pence a share although it adds some sources were skeptical about this.   The Sunday Times also said CSN was prepared to beat any offer from Tata and said the Brazilian company has increased the size of its loan facilities in order to give it greater financial leverage.   The U.K. Takeover Panel has imposed a Jan. 30 deadline for final bids for Corus.   Neither Tata Steel Nor CSN could be reached for comment.   Newspaper Web site: http://www.timesonline.co.uk   Newspaper Web site: http://www.observer.co.uk   -London Bureau, Dow Jones Newswires; +44 (0)20 7842 9320     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 21, 2007 10:00 ET (15:00 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: : Millicom International Cellular: SALE OF MILLICOM OPERATION IN PAKISTAN
Story: NEW YORK & STOCKHOLM, Sweden--(BUSINESS WIRE)--January 21, 2007--   Millicom International Cellular S.A. ("Millicom") (NASDAQ: MICC, Stockholm Stock Exchange: MIC), today announces that it has signed an agreement for the sale of its 88.86 per cent. shareholding in Paktel Limited to China Mobile Communications Corporation. The transaction implies an enterprise valuation for Paktel Limited of US$460 million. The total cash consideration payable to Millicom as a result of the transaction (including the repayment of intercompany debt) is approximately US$284 million. Completion of the transaction is subject to certain regulatory approvals and procedures. If such approvals are obtained, completion is expected to occur in late February 2007.     Commenting on the transaction, Marc Beuls, President and Chief Executive Officer of Millicom, said: "We are pleased to announce the sale of Paktel to China Mobile following strong interest from a number of parties during the sale process. The implied enterprise value of US$460 million for Paktel reflects fair value for the business. Completion of the transaction is dependent on regulatory approval. The sale of Paktel allows Millicom to focus on the 16 markets where we have already established strong market positions and, with penetration rates rising rapidly, the prospects in these businesses are good."     Millicom International Cellular S.A. is a global telecommunications investor with cellular operations in Asia, Latin America and Africa. It currently has cellular operations and licenses in 17 countries. The Group's cellular operations have a combined population under license of approximately 433 million people.     This press release may contain certain "forward-looking statements" with respect to Millicom's expectations and plans, strategy, management's objectives, future performance, costs, revenues, earnings and other trend information. It is important to note that Millicom's actual results in the future could differ materially from those anticipated in forward-looking statements depending on various important factors. Please refer to the documents that Millicom has filed with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission under the U.S. Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended, including Millicom's most recent annual report on Form 20-F, for a discussion of certain of these factors.     All forward-looking statements in this press release are based on information available to Millicom on the date hereof. All written or oral forward-looking statements attributable to Millicom International Cellular S.A., any Millicom International Cellular S.A members or persons acting on Millicom's behalf are expressly qualified in their entirety by the factors referred to above. Millicom does not intend to update these forward-looking statements.       Visit our web site at: www.millicom.com     This information was brought to you by Waymaker http://www.waymaker.net        CONTACT: Millicom International Cellular S.A. Luxembourg               Marc Beuls, +352 27 759 327               President and Chief Executive Officer               or               David Sach, +352 27 759 327               Chief Financial Officer               or               Andrew Best, Investor Relations, +44 7798 576 378               or               Cyrus Kapadia, Lazard, +44 20 7187 2000        SOURCE: Millicom International Cellular  Copyright Business Wire 2007     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 21, 2007 13:32 ET (18:32 GMT)

Headline: China: Injected $4 Bln To Recapitalize China Reinsurance
Story: BEIJING (Dow Jones)--China said Sunday it injected $4 billion from its foreign exchange reserves to recapitalize China Reinsurance (Group) Co., putting the country's biggest domestic reinsurer on track to launch an initial public offering this year.   Central Huijin Investment Co., a state investment agency charged with using the country's foreign exchange reserves to recapitalize the domestic financial sector, injected the money last year, China's insurance regulator said in a statement on its Web site.   Central Huijin's first-ever capital injection for a domestic insurer underlines Beijing's intention to expand the use of its massive foreign exchange reserves beyond the banking and securities sectors. China's reserves, at more than $1 trillion, are the world's largest.   At a meeting of China's top financial policymakers over the weekend, Chinese Premier Wen Jiabao said Beijing would "explore and expand the channels and methods for using foreign exchange reserves."   Central Huijin injected tens of billions of dollars into the country's four overseas-listed state banks ahead of their IPOs.   The state investment agency took stakes in other enterprises it has recapitalized, including banks and brokerages, though the statement issued Sunday didn't specify whether it took an ownership stake in China Reinsurance.   China Reinsurance, which had assets of CNY29.77 billion at the end of June 2006, has been targeting the introduction of strategic investors and an IPO since at least the beginning of last year.   China Re earned operating revenue of CNY12.57 billion in the first half of 2006, up 12.8% from a year earlier   Investors have displayed a strong appetite for stock of China's listed domestic insurers over the past year on Beijing's move to widen their investment channels and optimism over future revenue growth for the sector. Underlining that strong demand, shares of China Life Insurance Co. (2628.HK), the country's biggest insurer by premiums, more than doubled in their mainland China trading debut earlier this month.   China's insurance premiums rose 14.4% on-year to CNY564.14 billion ($72.5 billion) in 2006, the China Insurance Regulatory Commission also said in the statement issued on the commission's annual meeting held Sunday.   By the end of 2006, assets in China's insurance sector totaled CNY1.97 trillion, a rise of 29% from a year earlier, the regulator said.   Central Huijin is also finalizing plans to inject CNY24 billion-CNY25 billion into midsized lender China Everbright Bank Co., although the funds have yet to be put on the books of the bank, a person familiar with the situation said last week.     -By Rick Carew, Dow Jones Newswires; 8610 6588-5848; rick.carew@dowjones.com     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 21, 2007 04:21 ET (09:21 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: WSJA(1/22)Thai Banks' Earnings Are Hit By Bad-Loan Provisions
Story: (From THE WALL STREET JOURNAL ASIA)     By Supunnabul Suwannakij and Phisanu Phromchanya   BANGKOK -- Three of Thailand's leading banks reported annual earnings Friday, with two of the lenders hurt by increased provisionings for nonperforming loans.   Bangkok Bank PCL said its 2006 net profit dropped 12% to 17.85 billion baht ($507.1 million) from 20.31 billion baht a year earlier. Thailand's largest commercial bank by assets set aside 9.9 billion baht in loan-loss provisions, up from 4.31 billion baht in 2005.   Declines in 2006 earnings are expected at most Thai banks, mainly due to greater provisioning for potential loan losses to meet new international accounting standards called IAS 39, which were partially implemented in December. Full adoption of the standards is expected by year's end.   Net profit was pressured by a 2.94 billion baht tax expense. A waiver of the 30% corporate income-tax rate expired in the fourth quarter of 2005, the bank said. The tax waiver was granted to help companies following the Asian financial crisis of 1997.   However, the bank's net profit in the October to December period rose 3.4% to 4.05 billion baht, thanks to higher net interest income and 1.88 billion baht of investment gains.   The bank said its annual interest income surged 37% to 76.77 billion baht, while its interest expense in the year rose two times to 32.49 billion baht.   Bangkok Bank's nonperforming loans at year's end were 89.12 billion baht, or 9.24% of its total loan portfolio, down from 103.36 billion baht, or around 10.7% of total loans, at the end of September.   TMB Bank PCL, Thailand's fifth-largest bank by assets, reported a full-year loss of 12.28 billion baht for 2006, reversing a net profit of 7.8 billion baht a year earlier, mainly due to large provisions, the bank said.   The bank set aside provisions of 18 billion baht last year, mainly to comply with the Bank of Thailand's new accounting standards. The bank didn't say how much it set aside for provisions in 2005.   Last year "was considered to be a difficult year for the Thai economy given political uncertainty, high fuel prices, a strong baht and fluctuations in the market. All of these factors contributed to the unsatisfactory financial results," President and Chief Executive Subhak Siwaraksa said.   The bank said it plans to raise capital this year, in a move to strengthen its fundamentals in compliance with stringent new accounting standards. TMB declined to elaborate on its plan. Thailand's Finance Ministry, which owns a 31.1% stake in the bank, and Singapore's DBS Group Holdings Ltd., which indirectly holds 16.1%, have indicated their support of the bank's plan to raise its capital-adequacy level.   State-owned Krung Thai Bank PCL said net profit rose 8.1% in 2006 to 14.08 billion baht from 13.02 billion baht, on higher interest and noninterest incomes. Krung Thai said its interest and dividend income surged 34% to 67.47 billion baht. Noninterest income rose 39% to 10.11 billion baht on a 74% gain in investments to 1.31 billion baht from 75.3 million baht a year earlier.   The bank also booked expenses on bad debts and so-called doubtful accounts of 16.5 billion baht, up from 6.44 billion baht. Krug Thai Bank boosted its loan-loss provisions to comply with the new accounting rules.     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 21, 2007 16:30 ET (21:30 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: Shanghai Real Estate Tycoon Arrested Amid Probe -Report
Story: BEIJING (AP)--A Shanghai real estate tycoon was arrested Sunday on charges of bribery and using phony tax receipts, a news report said, amid a sweeping corruption probe in China's business capital.   Zhou Zhengyi, who was released in May after serving a three-year sentence for fraud and securities manipulation, was detained in October.   Authorities formally arrested him on Sunday, Shanghai-based Dragon TV said on its Web site. It gave no other details of the charges against Zhou, also known as Chau Ching-ngai.   Zhou once was one of China's richest businesspeople, with a fortune estimated by business magazine Forbes in 2002 at $320 million.   A sweeping corruption investigation in Shanghai has led to the ouster of the city's Communist Party secretary, Chen Liangyu. Other Shanghai officials have been detained.   Authorities haven't said whether Zhou's case is linked to those of Chen and other officials.   On Friday, Shanghai newspapers said authorities had detained 22 executives, including some from such major multinationals as McDonald's Corp. (MCD) and Whirlpool Corp. (WHR), in a bribery investigation.   Zhou also has been the target of lawsuits by Shanghai residents who say he failed to compensate them adequately for homes that were demolished in a redevelopment project.     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 21, 2007 06:30 ET (11:30 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: Air France Chmn Says Alitalia Chose Resignation's Timing
Story: PARIS (Dow Jones)--The timing of Air France-KLM (3112.FR) Chairman Jean-Cyril Spinetta's resignation from the board of Italian carrier Alitalia SpA (AZA.MI) was decided by Italian authorities, Spinetta said in a statement late Friday.   Spinetta resigned from the board of Alitalia, in which Air France owns a 2% stake, last week, citing the Italian government's plan to sell the struggling carrier as the reason.   "I made my decision to resign in early December," Spinetta said in the statement Friday, saying Alitalia and the Italian treasury were informed shortly afterward.   Italian authorities asked Spinetta to postpone his resignation until after a legal analysis of the move's consequences was completed, Spinetta said.   "After several weeks of waiting, on Saturday Jan. 13 the chairman of Alitalia asked me to send him my resignation as quickly as possible. That's what I did on Jan. 16, but only after also verifying that the Italian Treasury was in agreement," Spinetta said.   "The moment chosen to make public my resignation was therefore chosen by the competent Italian authorities," Spinetta said.   Late Friday Alitalia called a shareholders meeting for Feb. 22 to name a new board, after dissolving its existing board last week following Spinetta's resignation.   Alitalia's main shareholder, the Italian government, is seeking to privatize the company in a move to help it outline a new corporate strategy and end a run of several years of losses.   In December the Italian Treasury ministry published details of the tender for the sale of its 49.9% Alitalia stake. The Italian government will accept expressions of interest for Alitalia until Jan. 29.   Company Web site: http://www.airfrance.com   -By Greg Keller, Dow Jones Newswires; +33 1 40 17 17 40; greg.keller@dowjones.com     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 21, 2007 08:04 ET (13:04 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: UK PRESS: Google In Publisher Talks To Launch E-Books
Story: LONDON (Dow Jones)--Google Inc. (GOOG), the U.S.-based search engine company, is working on a service which would allow customers to download whole books to their computers, mobile phones or handheld devices, the Sunday Times reports.   The newspaper cites Jens Redmer, director of Google Book Search in Europe. Headline: Ex-Telecom Italia Chmn Denies Any Illegal Act In Spy Case
Story: MILAN (Dow Jones)--Marco Tronchetti Provera, former chairman of Telecom Italia SpA (TI), Sunday said he has never acted illegally or ordered illegal investigations, after his name appeared in a court document in a probe into alleged stealing of personal information.   In an open letter published by the Italian daily La Stampa, Tronchetti Provera reiterated that "never in my life, and during the course of my professional career, I've acted in violation of the law, either directly or by giving orders to do so."   Milan magistrates Thursday had ordered the arrest of three former Telecom Italia employees for alleged illegal espionage activities, bringing a fresh wave of scandal crashing down onto Italy's largest telecommunications operator.   The suspects were identified as Fabio Ghioni, the head of information security at Telecom Italia, consultant Rocco Lucia and former journalist Guglielmo Sasinini, according to a 230-page arrest warrant signed by Judge Giuseppe Gennari and widely cited in newspaper reports Friday.   A fourth warrant was served in prison on Giuliano Tavaroli, the former head of security at Telecom Italia, who had already been incarcerated on illegal espionage charges as a result of a separate investigation.   Milan-based magistrates are investigating alleged spying by former Telecom Italia employees in order to damage business competitors, businessmen and politicians.   Some of the people arrested are also accused of having siphoned big amounts of money from Telecom Italia, as apparent rewards for false investigations.   According to newspaper reports, the arrest warrant issued Thursday includes a statement from one of the people being questioned, which says that Tronchetti had taken an interest in some of the spying. The judge himself wrote in the warrant that the alleged stealing of personal information was to advantage Telecom Italia's controlling shareholder.   "I intend to repeat to everyone that the only fact, real and incontestable, that I am certain of is that never, and again never, did I order illegal acts to be carried out against anyone," Tronchetti wrote in his letter.   Tronchetti quit as chairman of Telecom Italia over a strategy row with the government last September, but he is still chairman of Pirelli & C. SpA (PC.MI), which controls Telecom Italia through holding company Olimpia.   "Never did I request illegal information, never did I receive or read dossiers against adversaries, competitors, people with different opinions, or even people openly hostile," he said.   The four men arrested Thursday are also accused of using Telecom Italia's resources to spy on Vittorio Colao, the former chief executive of RCS Mediagroup SpA (RCS.MI) - Il Corriere della Sera's publishing group - and on Massimo Mucchetti, deputy director of Il Corriere, as part of an elaborate intelligence operation.   Addressing this aspect of the case, Tronchetti said Sunday that, as representative of Pirelli in the shareholders' pact of Il Corriere della Sera, he always tried "to constitute a connecting element among the shareholders," in order to guarantee the independence of Italy's main newspaper.   Tronchetti closed his letter by saying he will continue to collaborate with magistrates in order to allow them to "search for the truth with the force of facts and evidence" and confirm his integrity.   -By Giada Zampano, Dow Jones Newswires; 39-3487678016; giada.zampano@dowjones.com     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 21, 2007 10:15 ET (15:15 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: GERMAN PRESS: Deutsche Bk CEO Ackermann To Retire In '10
Story: FRANKFURT (Dow Jones)--Deutsche Bank AG (DB) Chief Executive Josef Ackermann will retire at the end of his current tenure in 2010 and won't take a seat in the company's supervisory board thereafter, he told weekly magazine Der Spiegel in an interview to be published Monday.   German shareholders' association Deutsche Schutzvereinigung fuer Wertpapierbesitz, or DSW, which has been critical of the fact that executive board members often switch to the supervisory board after ending their management jobs, welcomed Ackermann's comments as an example of good corporate governance, daily Der Tagesspiegel reports, ahead of the interview's publication Monday.   Newspaper Web site: http://www.tagesspiegel.de; http://www.spiegel.de   -Frankfurt Bureau, Dow Jones Newswires; 49-69-29725-500     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 21, 2007 07:54 ET (12:54 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: FRENCH PRESS: Airbus UK Plants Risk Losing A350 Work
Story: PARIS (Dow Jones)--Airbus U.K. risks losing out to the aircraft maker's plants in Germany or Spain in securing a GBP100 million investment for the next generation of Airbus aircraft, the Financial Times reported Saturday.   Tom Williams, Airbus executive vice president of programs, said there was "certainly a risk" the investment wouldn't come to Airbus U.K. because the expertise to make large-scale components in composite carbon fiber materials already existed at Airbus plants in Germany and Spain, the Financial Times reported.   Airbus will decide within weeks where in Europe to locate the manufacture of the key parts of the A350 XWB, its new range of 270-350-seat, long-range jets.   Newspaper Web site: http://www.ft.com   -By Paris Bureau, Dow Jones Newswires; 33-1-4017 1740     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 21, 2007 08:32 ET (13:32 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: Siemens CEO Says Company Is Pulling Out Of Sudan >SI
Story: BERLIN (AP)--The chief executive of Siemens AG (SI), which has been plagued by corruption allegations, said in remarks released Sunday that the German company's policy must be to emphasize principles over profits and that it was pulling its operations out of Sudan.   Chief Executive Klaus Kleinfeld, who has hired an outside anti-corruption expert and a law firm to examine and revise Siemens' own anti-corruption safeguards, told Der Spiegel magazine there is a "zero tolerance for corruption."   He said this meant Siemens, Europe's largest electronics and electrical engineering company, would forego large contracts on matters of principle, and also pull out of countries on moral and political grounds.   "We're already doing that in Sudan," he said. "We have decided to pull out of our branches of business out of there - (and) not out of security concerns."   He didn't elaborate.   Six current or former Siemens employees are under investigation in Germany under suspicion of committing breach of trust against Siemens in cases stretching back to 2002 by setting up secret funds outside Germany.   Siemens said it identified suspicious payments involving some EUR420 million. Swiss and Italian prosecutors, who are also conducting investigations, suspect the secret funds were used to pay bribes to secure lucrative foreign contracts for the Munich-based company.     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 21, 2007 10:07 ET (15:07 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: Aiful To Halve Number Of Outlets To About 1,200 -Kyodo
Story: TOKYO (Dow Jones)--Consumer-loan firm Aiful Corp. (8515.TO) said Saturday that it will cut the number of nationwide outlets, including unmanned ones with automated loan machines, by more than 50% to 1,193 from the current 2,713 on a group basis to cut costs amid a tightening of regulations on loan interest rates, Kyodo News reported.   Aiful will also slash the number of full-time workers by 400 through voluntary retirement while cutting the number of part-time workers by 900, the company said in its restructuring plan endorsed at a board meeting the same day.   Aiful currently has about 7,000 full-time workers and about 4,000 part-time and temporary workers on a group basis.   The moves are aimed at cutting costs as the business environment is expected to become severer due to the government's plan to cut maximum interest rates on loans.     Aiful and other consumer financing companies are also facing growing demands by borrowers for the reimbursement of overpayments made under so-called "gray-zone" interest rates.   Under the restructuring plan, the number of ordinary outlets will be cut to 213 from 820 and while the number of unmanned ones with automated loan machines will be slashed to 980 from 1,893.   The restructuring will cut Aiful's operation costs by more than Y40 billion a year on an unconsolidated basis, the company said.   Gray-zone rates in Japan fall between two separate legal cap rates for consumer loans. The Interest Rate Restrictions Law caps rates at 15% to 20% according to loan amounts, while the Investment Deposit and Interest Rate Law allows higher rates of up to 29.2% to be levied on loans if borrowers consent to them in writing.   The Japanese parliament enacted a bill in December last year to lower the ceiling on consumer loan interest rates to 20% in late 2009 from the present 29.2% as part of efforts to help reduce the number of heavily indebted borrowers.   Since a Supreme Court ruling in January last year that effectively invalidated gray-zone rates, borrowers' claims for the reimbursement of overpayments have increased.     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 21, 2007 17:25 ET (22:25 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: Ladbrokes Buying Sponsio To Expand Nordic Online Ops
Story: LONDON (Dow Jones)--Ladbrokes PLC (LAD.LN), the world's biggest bookmaker, Sunday said it acquired its Nordic online gambling partner Sponsio Ltd. in a deal which could cost the U.K. betting firm up to GBP40 million.   Ladbrokes in a statement said it will pay GBP36 million for Sponsio, plus an extra GBP4 million if the Nordic gaming firm hits growth targets. Ladbrokes said the deal will be immediately earnings enhancing.   Ladbrokes signed a partnership agreement with Sponsio in 2001 to expand Ladbrokes' business in Denmark, Finland, Sweden and Norway. The Nordic countries together represent the biggest earnings region for Ladbrokes' online and telephone betting operations outside the U.K.   John O'Reilly, managing director for Ladbrokes' remote betting and gaming divisions, said in a statement: "Working with Sponsio has enabled Ladbrokes to become one of the leading online betting and gaming companies in the Nordic region. Having benefited from their local expertise, we are now consolidating our Nordic operations and will continue to drive successful online growth throughout Scandinavia."   Douglas Roos, currently managing direction of Sponsio, will head up Ladbrokes' Scandinavian division.   -By Lilly Vitorovich, Dow Jones Newswires; +44-0-207 842 9290; lilly.vitorovich@dowjones.com     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 21, 2007 11:02 ET (16:02 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: Softbank Mobile Suffers Another System Glitch Again - Nikkei
Story: TOKYO (Nikkei)--Softbank Mobile Corp. experienced another system malfunction Sunday evening, causing some shops to stop taking applications from new customers as well as requests to switch cellular phone handsets or change rate plans, The Nikkei reported in its Monday morning edition.   According to several sources, the order-receiving system that links each store with Softbank Mobile headquarters failed at around 5 p.m., apparently because of a processing capacity shortage. This caused stores to stop accepting orders, and some stores received orders but postponed handset delivery until the following day.   Softbank Mobile, a unit of Softbank Corp. (9984.TO), saw higher-than-usual customer traffic because it was the first weekend after the company started accepting orders last Tuesday for a new rate plan offering a low monthly basic charge of Y980.   Near the end of last October, a system glitch led the firm to temporarily stop taking applications to switch carriers under number portability. Although the new rate plan has delighted consumers, the series of problems may damage confidence in the telecommunications firm.     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 21, 2007 11:47 ET (16:47 GMT)

Headline: GERMAN PRESS: Volkswagen Seeks To Oust MAN CEO Samuelsson
Story: FRANKFURT (Dow Jones)--German carmaker Volkswagen AG (VOW.XE) is seeking to oust Hakan Samuelsson as chief executive of truck maker MAN AG (MAN.XE), the Der Spiegel weekly magazine reports in an extract ahead of full publication Monday. The report didn't cite its sources.   It said Volkswagen regards Samuelsson as an obstacle to its plans to contribute its Latin American truck operations in a possible merger of MAN with Swedish rival Scania AB (SCV-A.SK).   MAN approached Scania with a bid in 2006, triggering a heated takeover battle between Volkswagen, MAN and Scania.   Volkswagen Sunday declined to comment on the issue.   Volkswagen owns 34% of Scania voting rights and around 20% of MAN shares.   Magazine Web site: http://www.spiegel.de   -Frankfurt Bureau, Dow Jones Newswires; 49-69-29725-500     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 21, 2007 08:48 ET (13:48 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: WSJA(1/22) Shaping A Toyota-Ford Alliance
Story: (From THE WALL STREET JOURNAL ASIA)     By Norihiko Shirouzu and Jeffrey McCracken   Toyota Motor Corp. and Ford Motor Co. are sending more signals that they may want to establish deeper ties. But the cautious courtship between the two auto giants suggests a more modest, and less painful, approach than the megamergers of the late 1990s or the three-way alliance proposed last year among General Motors Corp., Nissan Motor Co. and Renault SA.   Speculation that Toyota and Ford might be edging toward some form of alliance has heated up since a meeting in mid-December between Ford Chief Executive Officer Alan Mulally and Toyota Chairman Fujio Cho. Both companies scrambled to play down the significance of that encounter, describing the meeting as a mere "courtesy." They stressed the talks produced no specific deals.   People familiar with the matter say the meeting was prompted by an invitation from Toyota, sent from Toyota's top brass to Mr. Mulally via a visitor to Dearborn, Michigan, where Ford is based, in mid-October. That messenger, a friend of former Toyota Chairman Hiroshi Okuda, met with Mark Fields, president of Ford's Americas operations, and gave him Mr. Okuda's invitation to the new Ford CEO.   Part of Toyota's aim in courting Ford is diplomacy -- an effort to win what people familiar with Toyota management's thinking describe as political peace from the U.S.'s second-biggest producer of automobiles. Although protectionist rhetoric has abated significantly compared with 15 years ago, Toyota officials remain concerned about a possible backlash as they continue to gain market share in the U.S. while Detroit's Big Three shut factories and ax jobs. Analysts widely expect Toyota to outsell Ford in the U.S. on an annual basis as early as this year.   Toyota also could benefit in a practical way if Ford agreed to use its gasoline-electric hybrid technology. That is in part because Toyota's momentum in establishing its hybrid design as an industry standard has slowed. GM, for instance, has lured German auto makers DaimlerChrysler AG and BMW AG into a powerful alliance to develop a hybrid system of their own that they say is simpler than Toyota's. Other companies, including Honda Motor Co., are trying to go it alone.   Messrs. Mulally and Cho, after talking for more than two hours, ended the meeting by agreeing to meet again soon, a person familiar with the situation said. A Toyota spokesman said no further meeting has been scheduled between the two but stressed that Toyota remains open to the idea of forming a tie-up to share costs of developing new technology or joining hands in popularizing new technology. Toyota also has shared operations with GM, including an automobile assembly plant in Fremont, California, that it has run jointly with the U.S. car maker since the late 1980s.   "So long as it is a win-win for both parties and there is a reason for partnering . . . we're open to the idea of forming a partnership. I think anyone among major auto makers around the world could potentially be our alliance partner," Toyota President Katsuaki Watanabe said in an interview in October.   Analysts say it is unlikely Toyota would seek to buy a stake in Ford, even though Toyota's market capitalization far exceeds Ford's. A primary obstacle is the 40% voting stock controlled by the descendants of Ford founder Henry Ford. Moreover, Toyota has generally avoided large scale acquisitions and alliances with rival auto makers. Ford, meanwhile, has too many financial troubles to buy a significant stake in Toyota.   Still, even the most efficient auto makers are worried about a glut around the world of auto-making capacity and surging costs to pack cars with new technologies in part to meet increasingly stringent safety and emissions regulations. Those concerns tend to spur interest in alliances that can help bring down component or raw material costs, or those for developing new technology, to give them an added edge.   Ford, according to a person familiar with its thinking, could be interested in a joint venture or partnership with Toyota that could focus on powertrain technology such as gasoline-electric hybrid engines or on smaller, four-cylinder engines, the person said.   The December meeting, at Toyota's guest house in Tokyo, was broad-based, and some senior executives at Toyota said Mr. Mulally talked a lot about his experience at Boeing Co., where he was the head of its commercial-aircraft division before joining Ford in September. He said he studied Toyota's lean-manufacturing process and transplanted some of the Toyota-devised production and inventory-control techniques like just-in-time parts delivery to Boeing's overall aircraft assembly operations.   Being a lean-manufacturing expert himself, those executives say, Mr. Cho was impressed by Mr. Mulally's knowledge. One of them said Messrs. Mulally and Cho "really hit it off," and predicted that their instant rapport may provide the springboard for a technical relationship of some kind.   "I don't know if Mulally-san realizes this," said one senior Toyota executive, "but if he asked for help or suggested a way to collaborate, knowing Mr. Cho, he would go out of his way to be responsive."   Ford, which has forecast substantial losses this year, has struggled to keep its engines competitive with other auto makers and in 2006 had to back off a much-hyped goal of building 250,000 hybrid vehicles annually because it realized it didn't have the capability to do so.   "Ford came out of that [Tokyo] meeting feeling Toyota was worried that politically there could be problems for it in the United States if Ford continued to struggle, so Toyota might want to do something that publicly looked like they were helping Ford, while it also marginally helped Toyota," said one of the people familiar with the matter.   This person added there would be more conversations in the future between Ford and Toyota about pursuing some sort of technology-sharing venture.     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 21, 2007 16:30 ET (21:30 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: Founder Of Swift Transportation To Buy Company For $2.74B
Story: PHOENIX (AP)--The founder of Swift Transportation Co. (SWFT) plans to buy the company for $2.74 billion, regaining control of the third-largest trucking company in America.   Jerry Moyes, who founded Phoenix-based Swift more than 40 years ago with his father and brother, said he reached a deal Friday to pay $31.55 per share in cash to take the company private. His group, which includes family members, also will assume $332 million in debt.   "I'm still a young 62, and I want to get back in the thrill of the hunt and get involved," Moyes said.   Swift shares closed Friday at $27.74 on the Nasdaq Stock Market, where they have traded in a 52-week range of $21.25 to $33.66.   Pending shareholder approval, the deal is set to be finalized in the second quarter of 2007.   Swift's board of directors unanimously approved the transaction, the company said.   "We believe the all-cash $31.55 per share price represents a fair value for the company and is in the best interest of all shareholders," Chairman Jock Patton said in a written statement.   The board had rejected Moyes' cash offer of $29 a share in November but left the door open for a higher bid.   Moyes said he had considered regaining control of Swift since being forced out as chief executive officer in October 2005 after an SEC investigation into insider trading. He paid a $1.26 million settlement without admitting or denying wrongdoing and was removed from his post two months before he planned to retire.   Through various trusts, the Moyes family still controls about 40% of Swift, according to Securities and Exchange Commission filings.   Swift Transportation began with one truck in 1966, transporting steel through the port of Los Angeles to Arizona and exporting cotton from Arizona to Los Angeles. By 1990, the company had annual revenue of $125 million and 800 trucks. It now counts 17,900 trucks and nearly $3.2 billion in revenues.     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 21, 2007 16:17 ET (21:17 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: Australia's Rinker Buys US Construction Materials Firm-2-
Story: Rinker's U.S. subsidiary Rinker Materials has an existing business in Portland, Oregon, which was acquired in 2002. Walling will be a "bolt-on" to the Portland operation, it says.   The Sydney-based company said the construction outlook in the region is positive, "with the housing slowdown expected to be offset by strong non-residential and infrastructure spending."   "Walling is a well-established business with strong market positions, and is a good strategic fit for Rinker Materials," Rinker Chief Executive David Clarke said in a statement.   Rinker, which now earns more than 80% of its revenue in the U.S., is currently fighting a US$11.69 billion bid from Mexico's Cemex S.A.B de C.V.       -By Susan Murdoch, Dow Jones Newswires; 61-3-9671-4393;      susan.murdoch@dowjones.com     -Edited by Paul Dekkers     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 21, 2007 17:29 ET (22:29 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.
